{{BLP sources|date=September 2010}}
'''Mark Handley''' is a playwright and screenwriter. He was born in Hollywood, California on March 5, 1956. He graduated from [[New Trier High School|New Trier High School East]] in 1974. In 1977, he and his wife moved to the Pacific Northwest where they lived in isolation in a log cabin that they built themselves. He is best known for his play ''[[Idioglossia (play)|Idioglossia]]'', which was later produced as Jodie Foster's film, ''[[Nell (film)|Nell]]''.<ref name="Berardinelli">{{cite book|last1=Berardinelli|first1=James |last2=Ebert|first2=Roger |title=Reel views 2: the ultimate guide to the best 1,000 modern movies on DVD and video|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=y1LmH8ld1yoC&pg=PT310&dq=%22Mark+Handley%22+Nell+Idioglossia&hl=en&ei=_Yt_TPSLFcv9nAe3l4DcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22Mark%20Handley%22%20Nell%20Idioglossia&f=false|accessdate=2 September 2010|year=2005|publisher=Justin, Charles & Co.|isbn=1-932112-40-5, 9781932112405|page=297}}</ref> Nell was co-written by Mr. Handley and British Dramatist William Nicholson (Shadowlands). Nell was the first production of Ms. Foster's company Egg Pictures and was directed by Michael Apted.  He currently teaches a screenwriting course in Seattle, Washington.

